00:07:47.800 --> 00:07:52.164
The next is that what I think
of a trendy web design is.

00:07:53.400 --> 00:07:55.919
It means applying three points.

00:07:55.920 --> 00:08:00.240
First of all, something that is not new,

00:08:00.302 --> 00:08:03.920
a trendy website based
on basic UX principles.

00:08:04.720 --> 00:08:06.169
These are the followings.

00:08:06.170 --> 00:08:08.011
Clear page hierarchy.

00:08:08.400 --> 00:08:10.797
Simple and consistent labels.

00:08:11.280 --> 00:08:14.920
Consistent menus
and layouts across the pages.

00:08:15.280 --> 00:08:18.799
Micro animations, such as hour effects.

00:08:18.800 --> 00:08:24.240
Loading indicators and responsiveness,
but real responsiveness,

00:08:24.330 --> 00:08:27.662
where all views retain full functionality.

00:08:27.760 --> 00:08:29.560
Just a side note.

00:08:29.840 --> 00:08:35.919
This principle what I've listed
is available in my speaker's note

00:08:35.920 --> 00:08:41.474
of my presentation that will be available
on the website of this event.

00:08:42.160 --> 00:08:43.879
My second point of trendy website

00:08:43.880 --> 00:08:48.480
is using advanced functions and features.

00:08:50.360 --> 00:08:51.599
Some examples.

00:08:51.600 --> 00:08:53.919
Making voice recognition and screen reader

00:08:53.920 --> 00:08:56.960
software compatible with the website.

00:08:57.280 --> 00:09:02.359
Integrating social media platforms,
such as Facebook, X, and YouTube.

00:09:02.360 --> 00:09:07.041
Using modern site interactions,
such as tabs and drop downs.

00:09:07.520 --> 00:09:11.249
Applying modern client
scripts like AJAX search.

00:09:12.320 --> 00:09:15.319
The good news
is that every function and feature

00:09:15.320 --> 00:09:19.120
can be implemented in an accessible way.

00:09:20.040 --> 00:09:25.440
Finally, trendy sites use
enhanced visuals like followings.

00:09:25.840 --> 00:09:28.319
High-quality videos and photos.

00:09:28.320 --> 00:09:32.799
Special effects like parallax scrolling,
simple, clear,

00:09:32.800 --> 00:09:36.080
and well-sized call-to-action buttons,

00:09:36.120 --> 00:09:41.359
organic shapes, flowing borders,
three-dimensional elements,

00:09:41.360 --> 00:09:44.760
and gradient and shadows as you mentioned.

00:09:49.160 --> 00:09:50.811
I listed four domains.

00:09:50.812 --> 00:09:54.960
General, colors,
dynamic elements, and targets.

00:09:55.320 --> 00:09:57.200
Where are they from?

00:09:57.640 --> 00:10:02.279
I made a list of 50 points
for creating an inclusive webpage

00:10:02.280 --> 00:10:05.479
but we don't have many hours
to go through.

00:10:05.480 --> 00:10:10.079
Therefore, I grouped them
into 10 categories and picked

00:10:10.080 --> 00:10:13.333
only the four most important to focus on.

00:10:13.920 --> 00:10:17.880
Now I can spend 7 minutes on each one.

00:10:18.080 --> 00:10:21.600
At the end, I'll provide
you with resources

00:10:21.650 --> 00:10:24.047
where you can go on learning.

00:10:29.520 --> 00:10:32.600
The first area, general guidelines.

00:10:34.720 --> 00:10:36.440
Know your users.

00:10:37.080 --> 00:10:41.285
You need to know more than just
WCAG success criteria.

00:10:41.920 --> 00:10:46.440
You also need to understand
different abilities of users.

00:10:47.280 --> 00:10:51.819
I mean different abilities,
not disabilities.

00:10:52.480 --> 00:10:55.440
Accessibility is for everyone.

00:10:56.000 --> 00:10:59.759
If there are blocking errors,
some users can't use your website

00:10:59.760 --> 00:11:04.600
at all and many other people
find it more difficult to use.

00:11:05.160 --> 00:11:10.879
There are many users whose abilities
are different from an average user.

00:11:10.880 --> 00:11:12.959
However, they are not disabled.

00:11:12.960 --> 00:11:19.479
For example, users with dyslexia,
colorblindness like me,

00:11:19.480 --> 00:11:24.879
hearing impairment,
ADHD, many people have.

00:11:24.880 --> 00:11:31.559
Autism spectrum disorder,
just a broken arm, or a headache.

00:11:31.560 --> 00:11:33.879
A headache can make it hard to think.

00:11:33.880 --> 00:11:37.999
You might throw your phone
out of the window if you can't solve

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:40.727
the reCAPTCHA for the fifth time.

00:11:41.280 --> 00:11:46.079
In addition, there are many special
circumstances that require

00:11:46.080 --> 00:11:50.760
inclusive design like browsing
on a sunny beach,

00:11:51.720 --> 00:11:54.656
watching a video in a silent library,

00:11:54.800 --> 00:11:57.815
using a laptop with a broken touchpad.

00:11:58.480 --> 00:12:00.959
These examples are only a few.

00:12:00.960 --> 00:12:03.019
You can find more than 100

00:12:03.020 --> 00:12:06.273
on the speaker's note of my presentation.

00:12:07.320 --> 00:12:11.200
All right, let's talk
about the disabilities now.

00:12:11.240 --> 00:12:13.471
These can be very distinct.

00:12:13.920 --> 00:12:16.319
The Paralympics finished a month ago.

00:12:16.320 --> 00:12:18.479
You may have watched some competition.

00:12:18.480 --> 00:12:20.399
I enjoyed the wheelchair rugby.

00:12:20.400 --> 00:12:23.479
They move fast like a bunch of cars.

00:12:23.480 --> 00:12:27.999
The classification has 67 categories,
each different.

00:12:28.073 --> 00:12:34.740
For example, athletes in T11
and T12 can run only with a guide.

00:12:35.440 --> 00:12:38.210
Lack of screen reader
support on your sides

00:12:38.211 --> 00:12:41.400
creates a blocking barrier for them.

00:12:42.480 --> 00:12:45.159
Some people are born with disabilities,

00:12:45.160 --> 00:12:48.334
while others acquire them later in life.

00:12:49.140 --> 00:12:53.028
Disabilities can be either
permanent or temporary.

00:12:53.640 --> 00:12:58.799
One thing they all have in common
is that when a person visits

00:12:58.800 --> 00:13:04.799
a website and encounters
difficulty with a basic contact form,

00:13:04.800 --> 00:13:08.360
it can result in feelings of humiliation.

00:13:09.960 --> 00:13:16.680
In 1997, Tim Berners-Lee,
the inventor of the World Wide Web said,

00:13:17.280 --> 00:13:20.771
'The power of the Web
is in its universality.

00:13:22.120 --> 00:13:27.594
Access by everyone, regardless
of disability, is an essential aspect."

00:13:31.080 --> 00:13:34.079
How shall we start designing for everyone?

00:13:34.080 --> 00:13:36.160
How early shall we start?

00:13:36.240 --> 00:13:40.159
We should start from the definition
of the goals and objectives.

00:13:40.160 --> 00:13:43.171
Here is an example for a good definition.

00:13:43.172 --> 00:13:48.520
Websites we design
will maximize accessibility and UX.

00:13:50.320 --> 00:13:53.649
I will go into the details
into user stories.

00:13:53.650 --> 00:13:56.879
Although some designers may not use them,

00:13:56.880 --> 00:13:59.895
I want to illustrate their usefulness.

00:14:01.440 --> 00:14:04.599
If you want to create
a professional website,

00:14:04.600 --> 00:14:09.439
user stories are the best place
to outline all your expectations,

00:14:09.440 --> 00:14:11.685
including accessibility.

00:14:12.280 --> 00:14:14.879
I give you some examples
that how are these coming

00:14:14.880 --> 00:14:17.607
from the knowledge of your users.

00:14:17.920 --> 00:14:21.559
The template of the user story
is the following.

00:14:21.560 --> 00:14:27.160
As a user, I want to do something,
so I can do that.

00:14:27.800 --> 00:14:33.560
As a deaf user, I want all website
videos to have accurate captions,

00:14:33.720 --> 00:14:37.320
so I can follow the audio content.

00:14:37.720 --> 00:14:42.800
As a user working outdoors
in bright sunlight on a mobile phone,

00:14:42.960 --> 00:14:46.439
I want the website to have enough
color contrast,

00:14:46.440 --> 00:14:50.640
so I can get the phone number
of the desired service.

00:14:51.360 --> 00:14:52.599
As a colorblind user,

00:14:52.600 --> 00:14:56.959
I want information presented
in ways other than just color,

00:14:56.960 --> 00:14:59.906
so I can book a seat without help.

00:15:00.600 --> 00:15:03.119
As a blind user,
I want the website to work

00:15:03.120 --> 00:15:05.879
fully with my screen reader,

00:15:05.880 --> 00:15:11.800
so I can navigate
into another page of the website.

00:15:13.400 --> 00:15:16.653
Again, more examples in a speaker's mode.

00:15:17.520 --> 00:15:20.759
If you consider
the specific needs of your users

00:15:20.760 --> 00:15:24.759
at the very beginning
of the design process, you will end up

00:15:24.760 --> 00:15:28.172
with a product that can be used
by everyone.

00:15:29.520 --> 00:15:34.079
Just to imagine the absurdity
of some accessibility plugins,

00:15:34.080 --> 00:15:37.000
here is a fictitious user story.

00:15:37.800 --> 00:15:43.679
As a user with cognitive impairment,
I want the border of all targets,

00:15:43.680 --> 00:15:48.280
so I can activate
the cognitive disability profile.

00:15:51.669 --> 00:15:54.399
Go another key point
in the general section,

00:15:54.400 --> 00:15:59.680
construct the best design processes,
and choose the best tools.

00:16:00.680 --> 00:16:02.519
Some design tools, such as Stigma,

00:16:02.520 --> 00:16:07.267
offer strong accessibility features,
while others don't.

00:16:07.480 --> 00:16:10.519
Choosing the right tools
can save money and ensure

00:16:10.520 --> 00:16:14.725
that your design
is on the right track from the start.

00:16:15.040 --> 00:16:18.199
I'm not going to talk about
the shift left process here,

00:16:18.200 --> 00:16:21.197
because you are probably aware
that catching

00:16:21.198 --> 00:16:27.120
errors late increases
cost really significantly.

00:16:28.040 --> 00:16:33.240
If an acceptance test uncovers
a problem caused by poor design,

00:16:33.680 --> 00:16:35.994
it would cost 40 times more.

00:16:37.200 --> 00:16:39.279
I give you a best practice.

00:16:39.280 --> 00:16:42.879
To make a team of your front-end
developers more efficient,

00:16:42.880 --> 00:16:46.640
establish a clear token naming convention.

00:16:47.280 --> 00:16:51.080
This is for translating
visual design into code.

00:16:52.000 --> 00:16:57.760
Design tokens are design decisions
that are translated into data.

00:16:58.960 --> 00:17:00.239
Using this,

00:17:00.240 --> 00:17:04.799
developers should be able to look
at the design file and easily find

00:17:04.800 --> 00:17:10.116
the specific design tokens
for a simple name of typography elements.

00:17:12.000 --> 00:17:15.799
This can be instructions, anything else.

00:17:15.800 --> 00:17:19.579
For example, design tokens represented

00:17:19.580 --> 00:17:24.000
in Figma by variables,
styles, or annotations.

00:17:24.840 --> 00:17:28.039
What kind of tokens can you add?

00:17:28.040 --> 00:17:33.760
You can add the accessible name
as annotations for a button with an icon.

00:17:33.800 --> 00:17:37.479
You can add a user preference
token to a dynamic element

00:17:37.480 --> 00:17:41.480
that keep disabled
by a user preference settings.

00:17:42.040 --> 00:17:46.086
You can add a token
for the name of the main region.

00:17:46.200 --> 00:17:50.879
These tokens can be added
by an accessibility designer or expert.

00:17:50.880 --> 00:17:55.679
Without them, developers
have to figure things out for themselves,

00:17:55.680 --> 00:17:59.012
which can lead to errors and higher costs.

00:18:00.000 --> 00:18:03.239
As many of you have noticed,

00:18:03.240 --> 00:18:08.120
I said that designers also need
to be aware of accessibility.

00:18:09.080 --> 00:18:12.239
Having the right knowledge
can significantly reduce

00:18:12.240 --> 00:18:15.652
the cost of developing
a conforming product.

00:18:17.000 --> 00:18:20.839
It's a good idea to bring
in an accessibility expert to help

00:18:20.840 --> 00:18:22.959
the product owner to clarify

00:18:22.960 --> 00:18:27.720
the definition of done
and also to review tasks.

00:18:32.200 --> 00:18:33.800
Use of colors.

00:18:35.480 --> 00:18:41.079
In my introduction, I've already mentioned
the rule that information

00:18:41.080 --> 00:18:46.280
should be conveyed in different
sensory types, not only colors.

00:18:46.960 --> 00:18:52.560
This lets 10 to 20% more users
be satisfied with your website.

00:18:53.160 --> 00:18:57.920
The wording of the related success
criteria is the following.

00:18:58.000 --> 00:19:02.999
Color is not used as the only visual
means of conveying information,

00:19:03.000 --> 00:19:06.479
indicating an action,
prompting a response,

00:19:06.480 --> 00:19:09.373
or distinguishing a visual element.

00:19:10.153 --> 00:19:13.679
Colors are not enough,
but what are the other visual means?

00:19:13.680 --> 00:19:16.919
These can be symbols, size, patterns,

00:19:16.920 --> 00:19:22.880
shapes, borders, tooltips,
lines, fonts, and so on.

00:19:28.440 --> 00:19:31.759
Without going into details,
I recommend the very best practice

00:19:31.760 --> 00:19:34.854
when starting a new design or redesign.

00:19:35.320 --> 00:19:38.047
Make the color palette inclusive.

00:19:38.280 --> 00:19:40.839
If you create the right colors
at the very beginning,

00:19:40.840 --> 00:19:44.520
you won't have to worry too much about

00:19:46.640 --> 00:19:50.200
the contrast later
in the redesign process.

00:19:51.920 --> 00:19:53.046
Let's say your primary brand color

00:19:53.047 --> 00:19:55.279
is deep blue with a slight greenish tinge.

00:19:55.280 --> 00:19:57.879
This color works
well on a white background

00:19:57.880 --> 00:20:01.119
and can be used for either
a background or a text.

00:20:01.120 --> 00:20:04.079
The secondary color is a light cyan
that has a contrast ratio

00:20:04.080 --> 00:20:08.880
of 1.58 to 1 to the primary brand color.

00:20:08.973 --> 00:20:11.159
We need to find a third that is suitable

00:20:11.160 --> 00:20:14.199
for indicating different states
of components.

00:20:14.200 --> 00:20:16.999
For example, in a radial bottom circle,

00:20:17.000 --> 00:20:20.174
a checkbox square, or a focus indicator.

00:20:20.680 --> 00:20:25.520
This needs to have a 3 to 1 contrast
ratio to the brand color.

00:20:25.920 --> 00:20:28.647
This pink would be good for that.

00:20:30.280 --> 00:20:32.639
Now comes the hardest part.

00:20:32.640 --> 00:20:36.954
We need to choose two different colors
for the link and the text.

00:20:36.955 --> 00:20:42.719
Both need a contrast ratio
of 1.5 to 1 to white

00:20:42.720 --> 00:20:46.240
and a contrast ratio
of 3 to 1 to each other.

00:20:47.657 --> 00:20:50.039
Adding color pairs to your color palette

00:20:50.040 --> 00:20:53.531
makes it easier to apply
them to your design.

00:20:56.160 --> 00:20:58.309
Some other considerations.

00:20:58.800 --> 00:21:03.799
Trendy designs often use
gradient backgrounds for text,

00:21:03.800 --> 00:21:09.116
especially in key areas such
as headlines or call-to-action buttons.

00:21:09.160 --> 00:21:11.279
Smooth gradients with gentler transitions

00:21:11.280 --> 00:21:14.519
are less likely to interfere
with readability.

00:21:14.520 --> 00:21:16.919
Avoid complex backgrounds or patterns

00:21:16.920 --> 00:21:22.077
to the text because it can make reading
more difficult and slower.

00:21:22.440 --> 00:21:26.239
According to WCAG,
the use of gradient is acceptable

00:21:26.240 --> 00:21:30.842
as long as all the colors meet
the required contrast ratio.

00:21:32.503 --> 00:21:38.040
Another best practice
which definitely works in the long run,

00:21:38.680 --> 00:21:44.640
create a second palette
with limited and reversed colors.

00:21:44.960 --> 00:21:49.360
You can use the same tokens
as the original palette,

00:21:49.440 --> 00:21:53.840
and developers
will be able to create it in no time.

00:21:56.040 --> 00:21:59.519
The second theme will be used
in the preferred colors scheme.

00:21:59.520 --> 00:22:01.799
This is a new CSS
feature that is supported

00:22:01.800 --> 00:22:04.362
by all major operating systems.

00:22:04.520 --> 00:22:07.799
The reason is that many people
use dark mode,

00:22:07.800 --> 00:22:09.919
and by creating this second theme,

00:22:09.920 --> 00:22:14.284
your dark mode users will get
the site with your colors.

00:22:15.880 --> 00:22:17.619
I need to talk about the relationship

00:22:17.620 --> 00:22:20.430
between color and visual overload.

00:22:20.920 --> 00:22:26.279
The question is, should that design
be simple or full of information?

00:22:26.280 --> 00:22:29.005
Some users suffer from visual overload

00:22:29.006 --> 00:22:33.159
when there is a lot of text and links

00:22:33.160 --> 00:22:38.080
on a page but in many cases,
this is a necessity.

00:22:38.640 --> 00:22:43.199
Look at a webshop that requires
many visual elements such as badges,

00:22:43.200 --> 00:22:46.100
reviews, and additional information.

00:22:46.760 --> 00:22:51.920
It's a fact that too much
information can overwhelm users.

00:22:52.120 --> 00:22:55.679
A clean and simple
layout helps users focus

00:22:55.680 --> 00:22:59.171
while still delivering
the necessary content.

00:22:59.400 --> 00:23:04.200
Professional UX experts
are capable of solving this problem.

00:23:04.480 --> 00:23:07.439
They can categorize data into two groups.

00:23:07.440 --> 00:23:12.599
Some information should be hidden
because it's irrelevant to most users.

00:23:12.600 --> 00:23:14.939
Less important information
should be hidden

00:23:14.940 --> 00:23:18.719
by default and you can use
modern design elements

00:23:18.720 --> 00:23:21.758
to dissipate them upon user interaction.

00:23:21.759 --> 00:23:25.680
This can be tooltips, dropdowns, or tabs.

00:23:30.200 --> 00:23:32.610
If your design meets
these UX expectations,

00:23:32.611 --> 00:23:36.959
you don't need to use
too many colors or too little contrast.

00:23:36.960 --> 00:23:42.752
Finally, remember that non-HTML
contents also need to meet contrast ratio.

00:23:48.920 --> 00:23:50.600
Dynamic contents.

00:23:51.720 --> 00:23:54.588
Let's turn to our third domain,
dynamic contents.

00:23:54.589 --> 00:23:57.604
No website can be trendy without them.

00:23:57.640 --> 00:24:00.080
I show you some key points.

00:24:01.560 --> 00:24:04.205
The design of perpetuum mobiles.

00:24:05.160 --> 00:24:10.920
Following components that play
automatically and run in an endless loop.

00:24:11.040 --> 00:24:16.919
This can be animated GIFs,
hero videos, advertising videos,

00:24:16.920 --> 00:24:23.040
slideshow carousels, marquees,
infinite scrolls, and so on.

00:24:23.280 --> 00:24:26.759
The basic principles to use
them freely in web design,

00:24:26.760 --> 00:24:31.080
but ensure that users
can easily control them.

00:24:31.560 --> 00:24:35.599
Many users leave your website
if they cannot control it.

00:24:35.600 --> 00:24:39.719
Here are a few creative
solutions to provide control.

00:24:39.720 --> 00:24:42.080
Stop within five seconds.

00:24:42.200 --> 00:24:45.360
Use controls like stop, pause, start.

00:24:45.680 --> 00:24:50.360
Delay autoplay
and let the user explore control buttons.

00:24:50.880 --> 00:24:53.839
Add an overlay requiring
a click or keyboard

00:24:53.840 --> 00:24:56.567
activation to start the movement.

00:24:56.940 --> 00:25:00.800
Use confirmation dialogues
to let the user decide

00:25:01.840 --> 00:25:04.319
and allow browser and operating

00:25:04.320 --> 00:25:10.000
system settings to control dynamic
elements based on user preferences.

00:25:11.760 --> 00:25:14.333
